1
00:01:45,772 --> 00:01:50,937
Warden, where does that fellow
with the guitar hang out?

2
00:01:52,145 --> 00:01:54,511
Down there, at the other end
of the prison.

3
00:01:54,581 --> 00:01:57,345
- I'd like to see him for a while.
- Well, Hart, you know...

4
00:01:57,417 --> 00:02:01,114
I'm the star boarder of this hotel
tonight. You're supposed to cater to me.

5
00:02:01,187 --> 00:02:04,156
Yes, I know. But once you leave your
cell, according to regulations...

6
00:02:04,224 --> 00:02:06,852
Oh, you can't be too technical
at a time like this.

7
00:02:08,261 --> 00:02:11,162
I can't see that it'd do any harm,
Warden.

8
00:02:13,166 --> 00:02:16,135
All right. But just
for a minute, remember.

9
00:02:29,816 --> 00:02:31,408
Hart's the name.

10
00:02:34,854 --> 00:02:37,880
Yeah, I know.
I'm glad to meet you, Hart.

11
00:02:37,957 --> 00:02:39,584
Mine's Poole, Larry Poole.

12
00:02:40,493 --> 00:02:42,961
Much obliged for the music.

13
00:02:43,029 --> 00:02:45,793
You sure tease pretty tunes
out of that guitar.

14
00:02:45,865 --> 00:02:49,426
Oh, that's not a guitar.
It's a lute, 13th century lute.

15
00:02:49,502 --> 00:02:51,629
Whatever it is, you sure got it locked.

16
00:02:51,704 --> 00:02:54,696
And you got a swell pair of pipes too.

17
00:02:54,774 --> 00:02:57,766
Many's the time I heard you out there
in the yard.

18
00:02:57,844 --> 00:03:01,075
It kind of took my mind off things.

19
00:03:01,147 --> 00:03:04,139
The chaplain tells me
you're due out of here next week.

20
00:03:04,217 --> 00:03:06,515
Where do you aim to go?

21
00:03:06,586 --> 00:03:08,952
Well, it depends on the wind. You see,
with me, when I leave a place...

22
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:11,786
I get myself a feather
and toss it up...

23
00:03:11,858 --> 00:03:14,588
and whichever way the wind blows,
that's where I go.

24
00:03:14,661 --> 00:03:18,119
Swell. Let me toss the feather
for you this time.

25
00:03:18,198 --> 00:03:20,723
Here's a letter I want delivered.

26
00:03:20,800 --> 00:03:23,234
It goes to some people named Smith.

27
00:03:23,303 --> 00:03:26,295
They live somewhere around Middletown,
New Jersey.

28
00:03:26,372 --> 00:03:29,773
I don't know the address.
That's why I can't mail it.

29
00:03:29,842 --> 00:03:32,003
Well, why do you want me
to deliver it?

30
00:03:32,078 --> 00:03:35,514
Because you're the only guy around here
I can trust.

31
00:03:35,582 --> 00:03:38,574
Anybody that can sing sappy,
sentimental songs in prison...

32
00:03:38,651 --> 00:03:40,881
wouldn't double-cross
a guy taking his last walk.

33
00:03:40,954 --> 00:03:43,650
It's mighty important that
that letter gets to those people.

34
00:03:43,723 --> 00:03:46,988
- Will you deliver it for me?
- Why, I'll be glad to.

35
00:03:47,060 --> 00:03:50,496
Thanks. Gee, that's a load
off my mind.

36
00:03:52,565 --> 00:03:55,898
- So long.
- So long.

37
00:03:58,438 --> 00:04:01,532
Okay, folks. Let's go.

38
00:04:15,121 --> 00:04:18,181
<i>Come on, folks.</i>
<i>Six rings for a dime.</i>

39
00:04:18,258 --> 00:04:20,123
A dime, six rings.

40
00:04:20,193 --> 00:04:24,687
Anyone can do it.
Come on, folks, six rings for a dime.

41
00:04:24,764 --> 00:04:26,698
A dime, six rings.

42
00:04:26,766 --> 00:04:29,633
There you are.
Six rings for a dime, folks.

43
00:04:31,971 --> 00:04:34,166
Six rings for a dime.

44
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:36,834
Step right up and ring 'em
and take home a present.

45
00:04:36,909 --> 00:04:38,240
Hold it.

46
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:42,881
- What are you after?
- Them.

47
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:46,415
Can't be done.

48
00:04:46,486 --> 00:04:47,919
Here.

49
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:52,716
Hey, what's the idea?

50
00:04:55,495 --> 00:04:57,224
You see there?
No can do.

51
00:04:57,297 --> 00:05:01,097
- Oh, a wise guy.
- Sister, you see that cop over there?

52
00:05:01,167 --> 00:05:04,500
- Run on over and tell him...
- Now, wait a minute, pal.

53
00:05:04,570 --> 00:05:06,834
Them opera glasses must have gotten
there by mistake.

54
00:05:06,906 --> 00:05:09,841
- Mm-hmm.
- Here's your dime back.

55
00:05:09,909 --> 00:05:14,972
My dime? Listen, I've been coming here
every day since this carnival opened.

56
00:05:15,048 --> 00:05:18,506
I spent lots of dimes! Hundreds and
millions, and I don't want my dime back!

57
00:05:18,584 --> 00:05:20,347
I want those opera glasses!

58
00:05:20,420 --> 00:05:23,548
And those glasses you shall have,
unless you want to yell, "Hey, rube."

59
00:05:23,623 --> 00:05:28,151
Well, if she wants them that bad,
why, she can have 'em.

60
00:05:29,729 --> 00:05:33,825
There you are, sister.
Thank the nice man.

61
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,061
Thank you, you crook!

62
00:05:40,406 --> 00:05:43,773
Gee, aren't they elegant!

63
00:05:43,843 --> 00:05:47,574
Elegant? They're just the last gasp
in binoculars, that's all.

64
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:58,584
Hey, look. The ground comes
way up here.

65
00:05:58,658 --> 00:06:00,592
Look out you don't step on your chin.

66
00:06:01,794 --> 00:06:05,059
- What's your name?
- Larry. What's yours?

67
00:06:05,131 --> 00:06:08,567
Patricia. But my intimate friends
call me Sarge.

68
00:06:08,634 --> 00:06:12,502
Sarge. Oh!
Mind if I call you Sarge?

69
00:06:12,572 --> 00:06:16,167
No. You're the most intimate friend
I've got. I'm awfully glad to meet you.

70
00:06:16,242 --> 00:06:19,905
You're not half as glad as I am to meet
you. I've been looking all over for you.

71
00:06:19,979 --> 00:06:22,607
Took me almost three weeks
to locate you.

72
00:06:22,682 --> 00:06:25,674
Your name is Smith and you live
over here on Railroad Avenue.

73
00:06:25,752 --> 00:06:27,845
- How did you know?
- I was by your house this morning.

74
00:06:27,920 --> 00:06:30,980
The people next door told me
I'd find you here at the carnival.

75
00:06:31,057 --> 00:06:33,651
They said to look for a little girl
with a red feather in her cap.

76
00:06:33,726 --> 00:06:36,854
Said she had on a brown...
Hey! Hey, wait a minute!

77
00:06:40,767 --> 00:06:42,359
Oh, no, you don't.

78
00:06:42,435 --> 00:06:46,872
I had to check off 165 Smiths to find
you, and I ain't gonna lose you now.

79
00:06:46,939 --> 00:06:49,464
- Are you a cop?
- Do I look like one?

80
00:06:49,542 --> 00:06:52,602
Well, are you
an installment collector?

81
00:06:52,678 --> 00:06:55,408
- No, I should say not.
- Then what do you want?

82
00:06:55,481 --> 00:06:57,415
- I got something for you.
- What?

83
00:06:57,483 --> 00:07:00,646
Hadn't we better tell that to the head
of the family? Is there somebody else?

84
00:07:00,720 --> 00:07:02,984
My grandpa.
There's just me and Gramp.

85
00:07:03,055 --> 00:07:05,353
I tell you what we'll do then.
We'll tell your gramp.

86
00:07:05,425 --> 00:07:07,893
- If that's okay with you?
- Sure. And you can stay for lunch.

87
00:07:07,960 --> 00:07:11,691
- Gramp's got a nice big ham.
- Why, I'd love to.

88
00:07:11,764 --> 00:07:15,564
Oh, I forgot. Gramp gave me a dime
to get a loaf of bread...

89
00:07:15,635 --> 00:07:18,195
and I spent it on the rings.

90
00:07:18,271 --> 00:07:23,208
Well, if Gramp can furnish the ham,
the least I can do is furnish the bread.

91
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:26,040
Oops. I'm flat myself.

92
00:07:27,380 --> 00:07:29,473
Madam, I am temporarily
without funds.

93
00:07:29,549 --> 00:07:31,517
That's all right. We can eat
the ham without the bread.

94
00:07:31,584 --> 00:07:34,052
Oh, we'll get pennies enough for bread.

95
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:36,418
- Where?
- From heaven.

96
00:07:50,069 --> 00:07:54,301
<i>On a lonely road or sidewalk</i>

97
00:07:54,373 --> 00:07:57,740
<i>It doesn't matter where</i>

98
00:07:57,810 --> 00:08:01,576
<i>I've always felt that I'd walk</i>

99
00:08:01,647 --> 00:08:06,380
<i>Into my love affair</i>

100
00:08:07,820 --> 00:08:11,620
<i>And on that perfect day</i>

101
00:08:12,692 --> 00:08:16,128
<i>I'd say</i>

102
00:08:17,530 --> 00:08:23,059
<i>The breeze runs after you</i>

103
00:08:23,135 --> 00:08:27,333
<i>When you're passing by</i>

104
00:08:28,908 --> 00:08:33,174
<i>It wants to be near</i>

105
00:08:34,447 --> 00:08:37,939
<i>And so do I

106
00:08:38,885 --> 00:08:44,687
<i>The willow bows to you</i>

107
00:08:44,757 --> 00:08:49,160
<i>Forgetting to cry</i>

108
00:08:50,229 --> 00:08:55,098
<i>It waits for your smile</i>

109
00:08:55,935 --> 00:08:59,063
<i>And so do I

110
00:09:02,675 --> 00:09:07,442
<i>All the world's at your command</i>

111
00:09:07,513 --> 00:09:10,846
<i>What wouldn't it do</i>

112
00:09:12,618 --> 00:09:16,748
<i>For one look at you</i>

113
00:09:18,724 --> 00:09:24,594
<i>And I'm that way too</i>

114
00:09:25,331 --> 00:09:27,959
<i>The rose</i>

115
00:09:28,034 --> 00:09:32,528
<i>That you caress</i>

116
00:09:32,605 --> 00:09:37,042
<i>Is willing to die</i>

117
00:09:39,111 --> 00:09:44,048
<i>It loves you so very much</i>

118
00:09:45,751 --> 00:09:50,051
<i>And so</i>

119
00:09:50,122 --> 00:09:53,421
<i>Do I

120
00:10:04,036 --> 00:10:06,436
- Let's do it again!
- Oh, no, Sarge.

121
00:10:06,505 --> 00:10:10,635
You give 'em a little, they throw coins.
Give 'em too much, they throw eggs.

122
00:10:10,710 --> 00:10:15,204
- What do you suppose that means?
- Let's find out!

123
00:10:32,665 --> 00:10:34,565
- Patsy!
- Hey, Sarge!

124
00:10:34,634 --> 00:10:37,865
Wait! Come back here.

125
00:10:42,208 --> 00:10:45,871
- What's this all about?
- That's just what I want to find out.

126
00:10:45,945 --> 00:10:47,810
Come in.

127
00:10:52,251 --> 00:10:54,048
Don't come close to me.
I have a cold.

128
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:55,587
Okay, I won't.

129
00:10:55,655 --> 00:10:57,589
- Gesundheit.
- Thank you.

130
00:10:57,657 --> 00:10:59,887
What were you doing down there
in that yard with Patsy?

131
00:10:59,959 --> 00:11:02,359
Oh, we were serenading the world.

132
00:11:02,428 --> 00:11:06,797
Tell me something. What made that kid
take off like a rabbit when she saw you?

133
00:11:06,866 --> 00:11:10,302
Guilty conscience.
She's playing hooky.

134
00:11:10,369 --> 00:11:13,668
Bless you. Say, you know that oil
of balsam is good for that.

135
00:11:13,739 --> 00:11:16,503
Never mind oil of balsam or any other
kind of oil. Answer my question.

136
00:11:16,575 --> 00:11:19,009
What makes you so interested
about this kid? What is it?

137
00:11:19,078 --> 00:11:21,774
I work for the welfare department,
and it's my job...

138
00:11:21,847 --> 00:11:23,940
to look after the problem children
of this county.

139
00:11:24,016 --> 00:11:25,813
Oh, is Patsy such a problem?

140
00:11:25,885 --> 00:11:28,115
Problem? I've got 20 to look after...

141
00:11:28,187 --> 00:11:31,452
and she's more trouble
than all the rest put together.

142
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:33,822
- Bless you.
- Oh, stop blessing me!

143
00:11:33,893 --> 00:11:37,124
That child's supposed to be in school,
and I find her dancing for pennies!

144
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:40,131
What's the matter with that? It keeps
the kid out in the open, doesn't it?

145
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:42,599
Who are you? I've never seen you
around here anyway.

146
00:11:42,668 --> 00:11:44,431
I'm the last of the troubadours.

147
00:11:44,503 --> 00:11:47,301
- If you think this is a joking matter...
- I'm not joking.

148
00:11:47,373 --> 00:11:50,240
Seriously, I'm just a harmless guy,
the friend of man.

149
00:11:50,309 --> 00:11:53,005
I envy nobody,
and I'm sure nobody envies me.

150
00:11:53,079 --> 00:11:56,276
If I were you, I wouldn't get myself
into a temperature over this thing.

151
00:11:56,348 --> 00:11:58,908
- It's bad for your cold.
- Never mind my cold.

152
00:11:58,984 --> 00:12:01,509
- Not too close.
- I'm sorry.

153
00:12:01,587 --> 00:12:05,580
- Are you related to Patsy?
- No, just a friend of the family.

154
00:12:05,658 --> 00:12:08,593
Do you know that she's in danger
of being sent to an orphanage?

155
00:12:08,661 --> 00:12:13,257
I've been trying to prevent it, but if
this goes on, I don't see how I can.

156
00:12:13,332 --> 00:12:16,665
What's wrong with an orphanage? I was
raised in one. It didn't hurt me any.

157
00:12:16,736 --> 00:12:19,432
- It didn't do you any good.
- What's the matter with me?

158
00:12:19,505 --> 00:12:23,669
If you want my opinion, you seem to be
nothing more than a shiftless loafer!

159
00:12:23,743 --> 00:12:27,179
You seem to be nothing more than
a nosey, meddlesome busybody!

160
00:12:27,246 --> 00:12:30,181
If you'd been raised in an orphanage,
you might have learned manners!

161
00:12:30,249 --> 00:12:32,809
I'm sorry, perhaps I was mistaken.

162
00:12:32,885 --> 00:12:35,911
Perhaps you're not really a loafer,
even if you do look like one.

163
00:12:35,988 --> 00:12:37,956
Just what do you do for a living?

164
00:12:38,023 --> 00:12:42,119
Oh, I eat, drink, sleep,
and I mind my own business.

165
00:12:42,194 --> 00:12:46,255
That's a formula I highly recommend,
especially the last part.

166
00:12:46,332 --> 00:12:48,892
Well, here's your money back.

167
00:12:48,968 --> 00:12:50,959
Guess you just don't like music.

168
00:12:53,405 --> 00:12:57,774
Oh, say, I hope that cold
is nothing trivial.

169
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:23,564
- Hello, Gramp.
- Hello.

170
00:13:23,636 --> 00:13:25,570
I see the landlord's been here.

171
00:13:25,638 --> 00:13:29,369
Yes, he came with a couple of men.
They left a little while ago.

172
00:13:29,441 --> 00:13:31,966
Oh, this is Larry,
my most intimate friend.

173
00:13:32,044 --> 00:13:33,705
- What's your other name?
- Poole.

174
00:13:33,779 --> 00:13:38,910
How do you do? I'm sorry I can't invite
you inside, but we've been dispossessed.

175
00:13:38,984 --> 00:13:40,451
- That's too bad.
- That's all right.

176
00:13:40,519 --> 00:13:43,613
The furniture don't belong to us.
We never have to send it back.

177
00:13:43,689 --> 00:13:45,884
The installment people always
come after it.

178
00:13:45,958 --> 00:13:47,892
That's nice of them, isn't it?

179
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:51,123
Good to see that you're not put out
about being put out.

180
00:13:51,197 --> 00:13:53,131
No. It happens all the time.

181
00:13:53,199 --> 00:13:56,657
Sure. We move in one house and stay
a while till the landlord puts us out.

182
00:13:56,735 --> 00:13:59,863
- We never pay any rent.
- Of course that's only temporary.

183
00:13:59,939 --> 00:14:03,898
Pretty soon I expect to come into
a regular income of $200 a month.

184
00:14:03,976 --> 00:14:05,841
Quite ample for our simple needs.

185
00:14:05,911 --> 00:14:08,880
- Larry's gonna stay for lunch.
- Delighted!

186
00:14:08,948 --> 00:14:11,439
Provided you don't mind
dining in the open.

187
00:14:11,517 --> 00:14:13,985
Oh, no, I prefer it.

188
00:14:14,053 --> 00:14:16,783
- Won't you sit down?
- Show him the ham.

189
00:14:23,062 --> 00:14:25,326
- Ain't it elegant?
- Oh, a dandy.

190
00:14:25,397 --> 00:14:26,864
We won it at a raffle.

191
00:14:26,932 --> 00:14:30,333
- Hey, look! Miss Sprague!
- Beat it!

192
00:14:49,188 --> 00:14:51,315
Charming landscape, is it not?

193
00:14:53,092 --> 00:14:55,925
Patsy's very good at finding
such places.

194
00:14:58,163 --> 00:15:02,964
Say, Gramp, tell me something,
will you?

195
00:15:03,035 --> 00:15:05,094
Does the name Hart
mean anything to you?

196
00:15:05,170 --> 00:15:08,537
If you mean the criminal
who was recently electrocuted...

197
00:15:08,607 --> 00:15:12,839
- That's the fellow.
- His name does mean something to me.

198
00:15:12,912 --> 00:15:15,107
He is the man
who killed Patsy's father.

199
00:15:15,180 --> 00:15:17,307
He gave me a letter for you.

200
00:15:21,387 --> 00:15:23,321
Here it is.

201
00:15:31,297 --> 00:15:33,265
A key.

202
00:15:33,332 --> 00:15:35,061
What's it for?

203
00:15:35,134 --> 00:15:36,601
Read the letter.

204
00:15:36,669 --> 00:15:38,933
No, I haven't my glasses.
Will you read it for me, please?

205
00:15:39,004 --> 00:15:40,596
Sure.

206
00:15:46,178 --> 00:15:48,476
"You know I never meant to kill Smith.

207
00:15:48,547 --> 00:15:52,005
All the time I was in prison
I kept thinking about his family...

208
00:15:52,084 --> 00:15:55,076
and how they must have been
up against it after I killed him.

209
00:15:55,988 --> 00:16:01,426
So I thought I would leave all I have
to the family of this man Smith.

210
00:16:01,493 --> 00:16:03,620
It isn't very much.
Just an old house in New Jersey...

211
00:16:03,696 --> 00:16:05,994
that I used to use for a hideout.

212
00:16:06,065 --> 00:16:10,331
I hope it brings you better luck
than it brought me.J.C. Hart."

213
00:16:10,402 --> 00:16:15,465
No. No, I could never live in a house
that belonged to that man.

214
00:16:15,541 --> 00:16:19,375
Why not? Probably the only decent thing
he ever tried to do.

215
00:16:19,445 --> 00:16:21,777
Let him do it.

216
00:16:21,847 --> 00:16:23,781
Poor fellow's dead now.

217
00:16:23,849 --> 00:16:27,285
Look, you've just been thrown out
of your house, haven't you?

218
00:16:27,353 --> 00:16:29,913
Well, here's another one all set up
and ready for you to live in.

219
00:16:29,989 --> 00:16:32,890
Besides, you have to
think of Patsy, you know.

220
00:16:35,661 --> 00:16:38,357
Thank you, Mr. Cow.

221
00:16:38,430 --> 00:16:42,161
There's a postscript here on the letter.
Says the house is...

222
00:16:42,234 --> 00:16:46,136
"on a road off the main highway
about five miles out of Middletown."

223
00:16:49,141 --> 00:16:53,703
- Oh, bless my soul, child.
- Oh, dear.

224
00:16:54,646 --> 00:16:58,104
<i>Old McDonald had a farm</i>
<i>E- l-E-l-O</i>

225
00:16:58,183 --> 00:17:01,641
<i>And on the farm he had a duck</i>
<i>E- l-E-l-O</i>

226
00:17:01,720 --> 00:17:03,449
<i>With a quack, quack here</i>
