00:34:32,036 --> 00:34:34,834
We plan to put a lot of signs up
and down the state highway.

456
00:34:34,906 --> 00:34:36,601
Yeah. Signs like skeletons.

457
00:34:36,674 --> 00:34:39,939
And we propose to serve chicken dinners
at very reasonable rates.

458
00:34:40,011 --> 00:34:43,378
There will be music and songs
provided by Mr. Poole here.

459
00:34:43,448 --> 00:34:44,915
A little floor show.

460
00:34:44,982 --> 00:34:48,179
Have any of you thought of
a little thing like capital?

461
00:34:48,252 --> 00:34:51,278
Oh, we won't need any...
not for chicken dinners.

462
00:34:51,355 --> 00:34:53,915
I have it all figured out right here.

463
00:34:53,991 --> 00:34:56,255
All we need to start is two chickens.

464
00:34:56,327 --> 00:34:59,194
I mean a hen and a rooster.

465
00:34:59,263 --> 00:35:03,427
When the hen starts laying
at the rate of only one egg a day...

466
00:35:03,501 --> 00:35:05,867
at the end of the first week
we'll have seven eggs.

467
00:35:05,937 --> 00:35:10,431
Those seven eggs in turn will hatch,
and at the end of the second cycle...

468
00:35:10,508 --> 00:35:13,875
there will be 49 chickens.

469
00:35:13,945 --> 00:35:18,143
Oh, Patsy. How many chickens will we
have in three months at that rate?

470
00:35:18,216 --> 00:35:20,446
- 2,401.
- You see?

471
00:35:20,518 --> 00:35:22,782
It's simply a matter of arithmetic.

472
00:35:22,854 --> 00:35:25,846
There! Are you satisfied,
Miss Sprague?

473
00:35:25,923 --> 00:35:27,948
No.

474
00:35:28,025 --> 00:35:30,186
I still say what about capital?

475
00:35:31,295 --> 00:35:33,786
- What for?
- What for!

476
00:35:33,865 --> 00:35:37,562
Why, for kitchen equipment!
For pots, pans, knives, forks...

477
00:35:37,635 --> 00:35:42,538
We're not worrying about finances. Gramp
tells me he's coming into some money.

478
00:35:42,607 --> 00:35:44,768
- When?
- In the very near future.

479
00:35:44,842 --> 00:35:48,141
Any day now.
And regular income too.

480
00:35:48,212 --> 00:35:50,077
How much of an income?

481
00:35:50,148 --> 00:35:52,082
Two hundred dollars a month.

482
00:35:53,718 --> 00:35:56,312
Two hun... From what source?

483
00:35:57,255 --> 00:36:00,224
- The Townsend Plan.
- The Town...

484
00:36:04,929 --> 00:36:09,127
Oh, I see. Well, just for the sake
of argument, of course...

485
00:36:09,200 --> 00:36:13,193
suppose the Townsend Plan doesn't go
into effect until after you've started.

486
00:36:13,271 --> 00:36:16,069
- Then what?
- Your attitude is unfair.

487
00:36:16,140 --> 00:36:19,075
Of course we need capital.
Why don't you let me take care of that?

488
00:36:19,143 --> 00:36:21,134
How? Singing in backyards?

489
00:36:21,212 --> 00:36:23,476
Well, that's my problem.

490
00:36:23,548 --> 00:36:27,382
If we can get away with this thing, is
it all right? Will you leave us alone?

491
00:36:27,451 --> 00:36:30,011
Yes. I'll leave you alone.

492
00:36:30,087 --> 00:36:33,454
As a matter of fact, I'd like very much
never to have to see you again.

493
00:36:34,258 --> 00:36:36,624
You'd be surprised
how unanimous that is.

494
00:36:36,694 --> 00:36:38,924
Come on, group.

495
00:36:56,647 --> 00:36:58,842
Poor, homeless little chickies.

496
00:37:10,027 --> 00:37:14,020
Looks elegant. Looks real nice.
I couldn't have done better myself.

497
00:37:14,098 --> 00:37:16,259
- Looks effective.
- You bet it does.

498
00:37:16,334 --> 00:37:17,767
That'll be $25.

499
00:37:17,835 --> 00:37:19,769
Deliver it, will you,
and send me the bill?

500
00:37:19,837 --> 00:37:23,295
- That's cash.
- Cash?

501
00:37:23,374 --> 00:37:26,138
- I'll have to paint one myself.
- Wait a minute!

502
00:37:26,210 --> 00:37:28,678
You've got no license ordering signs
without you can pay for them.

503
00:37:28,746 --> 00:37:31,909
You're right. I did wrong.
You keep the sign.

504
00:37:31,983 --> 00:37:33,974
But I don't want it.
I got no use for it.

505
00:37:34,051 --> 00:37:36,986
Well, I do want it.
I've got some use for it.

506
00:37:39,290 --> 00:37:41,485
Say, do you like chicken dinners?

507
00:37:41,559 --> 00:37:43,857
- Well, yes.
- That's our out.

508
00:37:46,697 --> 00:37:49,791
Now, the Excelsior Company is putting up
$1,500 worth of supplies...

509
00:37:49,867 --> 00:37:52,836
in exchange for 25% of our business.

510
00:37:52,903 --> 00:37:57,169
Your estimate for the costumes for the
waiter and entertainers is only $1,000.

511
00:37:57,241 --> 00:37:59,175
But we're not asking you
to take a cut.

512
00:37:59,243 --> 00:38:01,541
We're gonna give you 25% too.

513
00:38:01,612 --> 00:38:04,274
And it's a grand chance
to get in on the ground floor.

514
00:38:04,348 --> 00:38:06,282
Ground floor of what?

515
00:38:06,350 --> 00:38:08,284
What's your secretary's name?

516
00:38:08,352 --> 00:38:11,014
Myrtle. Why?

517
00:38:11,088 --> 00:38:15,491
Hello, Myrt? Don't put any calls
through here for ten minutes. Right.

518
00:38:17,762 --> 00:38:20,731
Tell me, Mr. Arbuthnot, what do you
think of the restaurant business?

519
00:38:20,798 --> 00:38:23,824
Well, people's got to eat.
It's the best business there is.

520
00:38:23,901 --> 00:38:26,369
- Good! You're in it.
- Huh?

521
00:38:26,437 --> 00:38:28,803
Here it is a week.

522
00:38:28,873 --> 00:38:32,570
There ought to be a couple dozen
chickens, and there's only two.

523
00:38:43,087 --> 00:38:46,250
- Good morning, Mr. Poole.
- Hello, Henry. Make up your mind?

524
00:38:46,324 --> 00:38:49,657
Yes, sir, Mr. Poole.
But there's a little trouble.

525
00:38:49,727 --> 00:38:52,628
Trouble? Well, speak freely.

526
00:38:52,697 --> 00:38:55,188
You see, I got the boys together...

527
00:38:55,266 --> 00:38:58,702
and I told them you wanted us to play
the music for you at the restaurant.

528
00:38:58,769 --> 00:39:03,138
- That's right.
- We'd get ten percent of the business.

529
00:39:03,207 --> 00:39:07,541
- And that's where the trouble started.
- Don't you think ten percent is enough?

530
00:39:07,611 --> 00:39:09,579
Yes and no.

531
00:39:09,647 --> 00:39:12,013
Maybe it's enough,
and maybe it's too much.

532
00:39:12,083 --> 00:39:15,348
But you see, there's seven men
in the band.

533
00:39:15,419 --> 00:39:18,286
- That's counting you.
- Yeah, that's right. Counting me.

534
00:39:18,356 --> 00:39:22,383
And none of us knows how to divide up
ten percent by seven.

535
00:39:22,460 --> 00:39:25,588
So if you could just
only make it seven percent.

536
00:39:25,663 --> 00:39:29,360
Seven percent?
Henry, it's a deal.

537
00:39:29,433 --> 00:39:31,958
Oh, thank you, Mr. Poole!

538
00:39:32,036 --> 00:39:34,266
I told them cats
you'd do the right thing.

539
00:39:34,338 --> 00:39:38,866
Why, sure!
I'll see you later. Yes.

540
00:39:38,943 --> 00:39:41,503
What is the matter with them?

541
00:39:41,579 --> 00:39:46,243
I don't know. I've tried everything,
including prayer.

542
00:39:46,317 --> 00:39:47,909
- Are you Mr. Poole?
- Why?

543
00:39:47,985 --> 00:39:50,146
I have a telegram for you.

544
00:39:50,221 --> 00:39:53,384
- Collect?
- No. Prepaid.

545
00:39:53,457 --> 00:39:55,721
Well then, I'm Mr. Poole.

546
00:39:55,793 --> 00:39:57,351
Sign right here, please.

547
00:40:10,508 --> 00:40:12,373
Well.

548
00:40:12,443 --> 00:40:14,604
- I'll tell you what's wrong.
- Yes?

549
00:40:14,678 --> 00:40:16,612
- You see that one there?
- Yeah.

550
00:40:16,680 --> 00:40:17,942
That's a hen.

551
00:40:18,015 --> 00:40:19,915
Yes. I know. I know.

552
00:40:19,984 --> 00:40:22,316
- See that one over there?
- You mean the rooster?

553
00:40:22,386 --> 00:40:24,877
That ain't no rooster.

554
00:40:24,955 --> 00:40:26,582
What is it?

555
00:40:26,657 --> 00:40:29,820
Hey, what's going on here?
We're supposed to open tomorrow night.

556
00:40:29,894 --> 00:40:32,829
I find you gazing at a hen
and a rooster!

557
00:40:32,897 --> 00:40:35,092
- Two hens, Mr. Poole.
- Disaster.

558
00:40:35,166 --> 00:40:39,068
We've just discovered there can be
no increase in the poultry department.

559
00:40:39,136 --> 00:40:42,230
It's a beautiful time for that
to happen. What about tomorrow night?

560
00:40:42,306 --> 00:40:45,241
How are we gonna feed customers
with only two hens?

561
00:40:46,544 --> 00:40:49,172
Mr. Poole, when do you have to have
them chickens?

562
00:40:49,246 --> 00:40:51,840
We gotta have them the first thing
in the morning!

563
00:40:51,916 --> 00:40:54,942
First thing in the morning?
And how many do you say you need?

564
00:40:55,019 --> 00:40:58,250
- Gotta have at least 50.
- At least 50.

565
00:40:58,322 --> 00:41:02,190
How many chickens does each man have
to get when you need 50 chickens...

566
00:41:02,259 --> 00:41:04,318
and you's got seven men?

567
00:41:04,395 --> 00:41:07,956
Well, if each man got seven chickens,
that would be forty-nine.

568
00:41:08,032 --> 00:41:11,126
Forty-nine.
Well, I think we can do it.

569
00:41:11,202 --> 00:41:13,193
- You can?
- Yes, sir.

570
00:41:13,270 --> 00:41:18,139
If you do, I'll make it 14% instead of
seven. That's two percent apiece.

571
00:41:18,209 --> 00:41:20,473
- Now I know we can do it!
- Swell.

572
00:41:20,544 --> 00:41:22,478
I'll tell you just how
we're gonna go about it.

573
00:41:22,546 --> 00:41:26,607
- Yeah?
- As it gets dark tonight...

574
00:41:37,661 --> 00:41:40,391
<i>There's an old deserted mansion</i>

575
00:41:41,565 --> 00:41:43,692
<i>On an old forgotten road</i>

576
00:41:45,035 --> 00:41:49,335
<i>Where the better ghosts and goblins</i>
<i>always hang out</i>

577
00:41:52,076 --> 00:41:54,544
<i>One night they threw a party</i>

578
00:41:55,713 --> 00:41:57,806
<i>In a manner a la mode</i>

579
00:41:59,216 --> 00:42:03,880
<i>And they cordially invited</i>
<i>all the gang out</i>

580
00:42:05,422 --> 00:42:07,856
<i>At a dark, bewitching hour</i>

581
00:42:09,727 --> 00:42:12,423
<i>When the fun was loud and hearty</i>

582
00:42:13,831 --> 00:42:16,459
<i>A notorious wallflower</i>

583
00:42:16,534 --> 00:42:19,435
<i>Became the life of the party</i>

584
00:42:19,503 --> 00:42:22,802
<i>The spooks were having</i>
<i>their midnight fling</i>

585
00:42:22,873 --> 00:42:25,967
<i>Merrymaking was in full swing</i>

586
00:42:26,043 --> 00:42:31,504
<i>They shrieked themselves</i>
<i>into a cheerful trance</i>

587
00:42:32,249 --> 00:42:37,209
<i>When the skeleton in the closet</i>
<i>started to dance</i>

588
00:42:38,689 --> 00:42:42,557
<i>Now a goblin, he giggled</i>
<i>with fiendish glee</i>

589
00:42:42,626 --> 00:42:45,652
<i>A shout rang out from a big banshee</i>

590
00:42:45,729 --> 00:42:50,632
<i>Amazement was in every ghostly glance</i>

591
00:42:52,002 --> 00:42:54,800
<i>When the skeleton in the closet</i>

592
00:42:54,872 --> 00:42:58,501
<i>Started to dance</i>

593
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:01,875
<i>Now all the witches were in stitches</i>

594
00:43:01,946 --> 00:43:05,382
<i>While his steps made rhythmic thumps</i>

595
00:43:05,449 --> 00:43:09,351
<i>And they nearly dropped</i>
<i>their broomsticks</i>

596
00:43:09,420 --> 00:43:11,354
<i>When he tried to do the bumps</i>

597
00:43:11,422 --> 00:43:15,688
<i>You never heard such unearthly laughter</i>

598
00:43:15,759 --> 00:43:19,058
<i>Or such hilarious groans</i>

599
00:43:19,129 --> 00:43:22,098
<i>When the skeleton in the closet</i>

600
00:43:22,166 --> 00:43:26,068
<i>Rattled his bones</i>

601
00:46:06,063 --> 00:46:09,624
Thank you, ladies and gentlemen.
That cat don't want no more of me.

602
00:46:09,700 --> 00:46:12,294
I'm telling you that much.
Look out there.

603
00:46:12,369 --> 00:46:14,303
One and two!

604
00:46:23,213 --> 00:46:26,273
I made a deal to get my meals free.
See the boss.

605
00:46:27,718 --> 00:46:30,516
I don't pay any checks around here.
I'm one of the owners.

606
00:46:37,327 --> 00:46:42,196
<i>I don't know the art</i>
<i>of elocution</i>

607
00:46:42,266 --> 00:46:46,760
<i>I'm no good at thinking on my feet</i>

608
00:46:46,837 --> 00:46:51,570
<i>I make no poetic contribution</i>

609
00:46:51,642 --> 00:46:56,170
<i>Even when you offer me a seat</i>

610
00:46:56,246 --> 00:47:01,946
<i>I've thrown away expressions</i>
<i>one by one</i>

611
00:47:02,019 --> 00:47:04,487
<i>I'm at a loss</i>

612
00:47:04,555 --> 00:47:10,460
<i>And something must be done</i>

613
00:47:10,527 --> 00:47:15,555
<i>When we're in a friendly situation</i>

614
00:47:15,632 --> 00:47:18,192
<i>My conversation</i>

615
00:47:18,268 --> 00:47:20,600
<i>May not be smart</i>

616
00:47:20,671 --> 00:47:25,631
<i>But if we're to have</i>
<i>a perfect understanding</i>

617
00:47:25,709 --> 00:47:30,169
<i>Let's call a heart a heart</i>

618
00:47:31,515 --> 00:47:35,508
<i>There are words</i>
<i>that should be whispered gently</i>

619
00:47:35,586 --> 00:47:37,781
<i>That's evidently</i>

620
00:47:37,855 --> 00:47:40,847
<i>The way to start</i>

621
00:47:40,924 --> 00:47:46,055
<i>If I tell you what my dreams</i>
<i>have been demanding</i>

622
00:47:46,129 --> 00:47:51,362
<i>Let's call a heart a heart</i>

623
00:47:52,102 --> 00:47:55,503
<i>Can I prove how I yearn</i>

624
00:47:55,572 --> 00:48:00,009
<i>Just by the turn of a phrase</i>

625
00:48:00,077 --> 00:48:03,740
<i>Can I keep my control</i>

626
00:48:04,514 --> 00:48:09,816
<i>When all my soul is ablaze</i>

627
00:48:11,288 --> 00:48:16,282
<i>Maybe you would call</i>
<i>a true confession</i>

628
00:48:17,227 --> 00:48:20,162
<i>An indiscretion</i>

629
00:48:20,230 --> 00:48:24,564
<i>On someone's part</i>

630
00:48:26,470 --> 00:48:30,372
<i>But if I'm to say how madly</i>

631
00:48:30,440 --> 00:48:32,431
<i>I adore you</i>

632
00:48:33,543 --> 00:48:37,741
<i>Let's call a heart</i>

633
00:48:37,814 --> 00:48:41,545
<i>A heart</i>

634
00:48:54,331 --> 00:48:56,561
And let's call a spade a spade too.

635
00:48:56,633 --> 00:48:59,534
If your menu had any humble pie,
I'd eat it.

636
00:48:59,603 --> 00:49:02,629
I was wrong,
and I humbly apologize.

637
00:49:02,706 --> 00:49:06,107
There's no doubt about it,
the cafe is a tremendous success...

638
00:49:06,176 --> 00:49:08,144
and I didn't think you could do it.

639
00:49:08,211 --> 00:49:12,739
Oh, I had to. You made me do it.
Did you enjoy your dinner?

640
00:49:12,816 --> 00:49:14,807
- Very much.
- Music okay?

641
00:49:14,885 --> 00:49:16,716
Mm-hmm. It's delightful.

642
00:49:16,787 --> 00:49:18,584
- You like the looks of the place?
- Charming.

643
00:49:18,655 --> 00:49:22,989
Look. If I could show you where we could
put this place on a paying basis...

644
00:49:23,060 --> 00:49:26,655
so it could provide a comfortable income
for Patsy and Gramp...

645
00:49:26,730 --> 00:49:28,664
would you be satisfied?

646
00:49:28,732 --> 00:49:31,895
I'd be more than satisfied.
I'd be awfully happy.

647
00:49:31,969 --> 00:49:33,732
Then everybody'd be happy.

648
00:49:33,804 --> 00:49:35,465
- You too?
- Me too.

649
00:49:35,539 --> 00:49:38,167
'Cause then I'd be
on my way to Venice.

650
00:49:38,241 --> 00:49:40,675
Why are you so keen about Venice?

651
00:49:40,744 --> 00:49:43,008
Ah, you wouldn't ask that
if you'd ever been there.

652
00:49:43,080 --> 00:49:45,878
It's the most beautiful spot
in the world.

653
00:49:45,949 --> 00:49:49,510
Why, Venice has got all the postcards
you've ever seen whipped to a frazzle.

654
00:49:49,586 --> 00:49:52,783
You haven't lived until you've floated
down the Grand Canal in a gondola...

655
00:49:52,856 --> 00:49:56,155
especially on a feast day with
the colored lights and the flowers...

656
00:49:56,226 --> 00:49:58,660
and the people singing and laughing,
and guitars.

657
00:49:58,729 --> 00:50:00,458
You know a great deal about Venice.

658
00:50:00,530 --> 00:50:03,260
Were you by any chance born there?

659
00:50:03,333 --> 00:50:06,427
No. I was born in Mukilteo, Washington.

660
00:50:07,537 --> 00:50:09,505
But you've spent
a great deal of time in Venice.

661
00:50:09,573 --> 00:50:12,804
No. I've never been there.

662
00:50:12,876 --> 00:50:15,003
But I wanted to go ever since I was
a little sprout...

663
00:50:15,078 --> 00:50:17,308
but it looked as though
every time I got set to go...

664
00:50:17,381 --> 00:50:20,111
something happened
and sent me somewhere else.

665
00:50:20,183 --> 00:50:23,175
As, for instance, prison?

666
00:50:26,289 --> 00:50:27,916
How'd you know about that?

667
00:50:27,991 --> 00:50:31,085
I checked up. It was for my own
information, of course.

668
00:50:31,161 --> 00:50:32,890
I didn't let them know
at the office.

669
00:50:32,963 --> 00:50:36,364
I guess you found out
what I was in for, didn't you?

670
00:50:36,433 --> 00:50:38,867
Smuggling.

671
00:50:38,935 --> 00:50:42,496
Yeah.
That was on account of Venice too.

672
00:50:42,572 --> 00:50:45,040
See, I didn't have enough dough to take
passage on a regular ship...

673
00:50:45,108 --> 00:50:47,576
so I stowed away on a freighter...

674
00:50:47,644 --> 00:50:49,612
and they raided the freighter before
they got up anchor.

675
00:50:49,679 --> 00:50:53,809
Turned out to be a smuggling ship.
Judge wouldn't believe me.

676
00:50:53,884 --> 00:50:57,320
- I guess you don't either, do you?
- Yes, I do.

677
00:50:57,387 --> 00:50:59,719
You do?

678
00:50:59,790 --> 00:51:01,223
Well, come here.

679
00:51:06,063 --> 00:51:08,031
What made you do that?

680
00:51:09,099 --> 00:51:12,364
Oh, I don't know.
I just played an impulse.

681
00:51:13,570 --> 00:51:15,936
I guess I wanted to see
what it was like.

682
00:51:16,006 --> 00:51:19,100
It was swell.
Your lips are nice and cool.

683
00:51:19,176 --> 00:51:23,010
- You don't mind an audience, do you?
- Not in the least.

684
00:51:23,080 --> 00:51:25,344
Do you mind if I obey
an impulse too?

685
00:51:26,383 --> 00:51:28,613
Not at all.

686
00:51:28,685 --> 00:51:30,653
Good night, Mr. Poole.

687
00:51:33,290 --> 00:51:36,350
Check, sir.

688
00:51:38,228 --> 00:51:41,959
Just skip it, sonny.
I'm one of the big owners of the place.

689
00:51:45,102 --> 00:51:48,071
Say, mister, you better
get yourself a new waiter.

690
00:51:48,138 --> 00:51:51,665
I just figured out the checks,
and everybody seems to be a partner.

691
00:51:51,741 --> 00:51:55,142
The way it adds up,
you've sold 110% of this restaurant!

692
00:51:55,212 --> 00:51:58,670
I agreed to work here for my tips,
and there aren't no tips.

693
00:51:58,748 --> 00:52:01,410
The only paying customer was
that dame that just left.

694
00:52:01,485 --> 00:52:03,885
She gimme a dime.
Here, you take it.

695
00:52:03,954 --> 00:52:06,445
You might need it.
And here's your ribs.

696
00:52:08,358 --> 00:52:11,293
Might need those too.

697
00:52:11,361 --> 00:52:12,851
Good-bye.

698
00:52:25,242 --> 00:52:27,870
- You Mr. Poole?
- Yeah.

699
00:52:27,944 --> 00:52:30,003
You run this place?

700
00:52:30,080 --> 00:52:32,207
Well, in a manner of speaking, yes.

701
00:52:32,282 --> 00:52:34,045
Well, where's your license?

702
00:52:34,117 --> 00:52:35,778
What license?

703
00:52:35,852 --> 00:52:37,820
Don't you know you need
a tavern license...

704
00:52:37,888 --> 00:52:40,686
to operate an eatin' place
in this county?

705
00:52:40,757 --> 00:52:43,055
Drat. Now, how could I have
overlooked that?

706
00:52:43,126 --> 00:52:45,424
Certainly glad you dropped in
to remind me.

707
00:52:45,495 --> 00:52:48,293
Just what does
one of these licenses cost?

708
00:52:48,365 --> 00:52:51,493
$100, and you can't start
doing business without one.

709
00:52:51,568 --> 00:52:53,502
Well, naturally.

710
00:52:53,570 --> 00:52:56,300
Say, have you got a card
you can let me have?

711
00:52:57,908 --> 00:53:01,400
Thanks. I'll be down to take care of it
first thing in the morning.

712
00:53:01,478 --> 00:53:02,877
Okay.

713
00:53:03,947 --> 00:53:05,744
We open at 9:00.

714
00:53:13,723 --> 00:53:17,420
Oh, now looka here. You told me
you were gonna stay upstairs.

715
00:53:17,494 --> 00:53:19,792
Oh, I just couldn't stay up there.

716
00:53:19,863 --> 00:53:23,993
When I saw Miss Sprague leave, I just
had to come down for one little look.

717
00:53:25,635 --> 00:53:29,435
- Ain't it an elegant opening night?
- You mean "closing night."

718
00:53:29,506 --> 00:53:31,337
Sergeant, you see gathered
about you tonight...

719
00:53:31,408 --> 00:53:34,275
more deadheads than have ever been
collected under a single roof.

720
00:53:34,344 --> 00:53:37,836
And they're all in on rain checks.
The headwaiter just quit too.

721
00:53:37,914 --> 00:53:40,610
When our entertainers find out
what their percentage is...

722
00:53:40,684 --> 00:53:42,709
I have an idea
they'll also quit.

723
00:53:42,786 --> 00:53:45,983
We got bills up to here.
The tax collector was in to tell me...

724
00:53:46,056 --> 00:53:48,217
if we don't get a license,
he's gonna close us up.

725
00:53:48,291 --> 00:53:51,624
The license costs $100,
and we haven't got a hundred cents.

726
00:53:51,695 --> 00:53:55,153
Gee, what are we gonna do?

727
00:53:55,232 --> 00:53:57,200
Let's dance.

728
00:54:12,182 --> 00:54:16,084
- Madam, you know you dance divinely?
- Thank you. You dance elegant yourself.

729
00:54:23,526 --> 00:54:26,586
Good evening, gentlemen.
Some nice chicken dinners tonight?

730
00:54:26,663 --> 00:54:30,690
See? What did I tell ya?
There they are!

731
00:54:30,767 --> 00:54:33,565
Those are the fellas
that stole our chickens!

732
00:54:33,637 --> 00:54:35,901
Come on!

733
00:54:35,972 --> 00:54:38,133
Look out!
The law, gentlemen!

734
00:54:42,579 --> 00:54:44,740
What's the trouble?

735
00:54:55,558 --> 00:54:59,153
- If you let us have a little while...
- You're breakin' the law as it is.

736
00:54:59,229 --> 00:55:02,392
I'll give you only 24 hours
to get that license.

737
00:55:09,239 --> 00:55:11,173
There's no work
attached to it whatsoever.

738
00:55:11,241 --> 00:55:14,540
And the pay is incredulous...
a dollar a second.

739
00:55:14,611 --> 00:55:17,637
Thirty dollars for thirty seconds,
twice a day.

740
00:55:17,714 --> 00:55:19,841
Doin' what?

741
00:55:25,422 --> 00:55:29,916
You know, this guy Devlin I was usin' to
do these loop the loops, he was no good.

742
00:55:29,993 --> 00:55:33,394
No. In fact, he did me a favor
when he got cracked up.

743
00:55:33,463 --> 00:55:35,954
We're gonna get a lot
of publicity from this accident.

744
00:55:36,032 --> 00:55:39,763
And from now on, we'll do a world
of business. Well, what do you say?

745
00:55:39,836 --> 00:55:42,202
What do I know about
death in the afternoon?

746
00:55:42,272 --> 00:55:44,399
Don't pay any attention to that.
That's just the billin'.

747
00:55:52,716 --> 00:55:54,149
Hello?

748
00:55:58,822 --> 00:56:01,689
Hello?
Oh, hello, Larry.

749
00:56:01,758 --> 00:56:05,159
What? Over to the fairgrounds?
Patsy and me?

750
00:56:05,228 --> 00:56:08,664
All right. Yeah, surely.
We'll be right over.

751
00:56:12,602 --> 00:56:15,264
It's Larry. He wants us
to come over to the fairgrounds.

752
00:56:15,338 --> 00:56:18,102
He says it's a surprise.
Come on. Let's go.

753
00:56:18,174 --> 00:56:19,641
Wait.

754
00:56:29,352 --> 00:56:32,685
- Wonder where Larry is.
- He doesn't hurry, he'll miss the show.

755
00:56:36,993 --> 00:56:39,393
Gee, that's gettin' higher
all the time.

756
00:56:39,462 --> 00:56:41,589
- Which one loops the loop?
- The front one.

757
00:56:41,664 --> 00:56:43,655
Okay, I'll ride
the back one.

758
00:56:43,733 --> 00:56:46,133
- No. I've got a dummy nailed in there.
- A dummy?

759
00:56:46,202 --> 00:56:49,763
Yes. Listen, you got nothing
to be afraid of. It's child's play.

760
00:56:49,839 --> 00:56:54,242
- Why don't you do it yourself?
- Well, who's gonna make the spiel?

761
00:57:04,687 --> 00:57:08,145
Grandpa! Grandpa, look!
It's Larry!

762
00:57:20,603 --> 00:57:25,165
Now, ladies and gentlemen, I take
great pleasure in introducing to you...

763
00:57:25,241 --> 00:57:28,176
the one and only
Dare Devil Devlin...

764
00:57:28,244 --> 00:57:32,237
in the most daring act
ever conceived by mortal mind...

765
00:57:32,315 --> 00:57:35,910
or executed
by man born of woman.

766
00:57:35,985 --> 00:57:40,422
He'll thumb his nose, ladies
and gentlemen, at the Grim Reaper!

767
00:57:40,490 --> 00:57:46,019
He will defy death.
The one and only Dare Devil Devlin!

768
00:58:43,453 --> 00:58:45,182
Are you ready?

769
00:58:47,190 --> 00:58:51,058
- No, can't handle it.
- Okay! Let her go!

770
00:59:11,848 --> 00:59:13,782
Larry, are you hurt?

771
00:59:13,850 --> 00:59:18,549
No, I'm all right, Sarge.
I must've stubbed my toe.

772
00:59:18,621 --> 00:59:20,054
Don't worry, kid.

773
00:59:20,123 --> 00:59:22,785
- The hospital expenses are on me.
- Please, get some water.

774
00:59:37,807 --> 00:59:39,741
Hey, Gramp! Come on in!

775
00:59:45,682 --> 00:59:47,616
Well, what's the matter?

776
00:59:47,684 --> 00:59:51,051
What's happened?
Where's Patsy?

777
00:59:51,120 --> 00:59:53,418
She's gone.

778
00:59:53,489 --> 00:59:55,616
They've taken her away.

779
01:00:04,200 --> 01:00:07,328
An officer is on his way
to the orphanage now with the child.

780
01:00:07,403 --> 01:00:10,236
Yes, Miss Howard,
a most troublesome case.

781
01:00:10,306 --> 01:00:14,208
- I'm glad it's finally settled.
- May I be the first to congratulate you?

782
01:00:17,814 --> 01:00:19,839
Would you mind explaining
why you saw fit...

783
01:00:19,916 --> 01:00:22,646
to have a hearing about the Smith child
without telling me?

784
01:00:22,719 --> 01:00:25,119
We decided we didn't need
your help in the matter.

785
01:00:25,188 --> 01:00:27,884
This is my case.
You had no right to go over my head.

786
01:00:27,957 --> 01:00:30,619
I'm under the impression
that I'm still the head of this bureau.

787
01:00:30,693 --> 01:00:33,753
That may be, but it's no excuse
for what you've done.

788
01:00:33,830 --> 01:00:36,628
You took advantage of the fact that
Mr. Poole is lying in the hospital...

789
01:00:36,699 --> 01:00:38,462
to send that child to an asylum.

790
01:00:38,534 --> 01:00:40,559
It doesn't alter the fact
that he's a penniless hobo.

791
01:00:40,637 --> 01:00:44,505
No, he's not.
He's a free soul and lives a free life.

792
01:00:44,574 --> 01:00:46,508
I only wish I had the courage
to be like him.

793
01:00:46,576 --> 01:00:50,774
That gal did it. She took advantage
of the fact I'm in the hospital.

794
01:00:50,847 --> 01:00:54,180
And they left instructions
not to let you come to the orphanage.

795
01:00:54,250 --> 01:00:56,878
- That's part of the court order.
- Yeah.

796
01:00:56,953 --> 01:01:01,151
- She took care of that too, I suppose.
- Oh, my boy, please get back in bed.

797
01:01:01,224 --> 01:01:03,658
Remember, you're still in bandages.

798
01:01:03,726 --> 01:01:06,286
Yes, and that's her fault too.
Everything's her fault!

799
01:01:06,362 --> 01:01:09,695
Hadn't been for her, I'd be in Venice
now havin' the time of my life.

800
01:01:09,766 --> 01:01:12,326
I regret to have to say
this to you.

801
01:01:12,402 --> 01:01:14,666
Up to now you've been
a faithful and trustworthy worker.

802
01:01:14,737 --> 01:01:16,671
I know.
You're going to give me the air.

803
01:01:16,739 --> 01:01:21,039
I could do with some air. I never knew
till now how stuffy it is in here.

804
01:01:41,197 --> 01:01:44,132
You don't have to
run away from me now.

805
01:01:45,334 --> 01:01:47,700
- What do you want?
- I want to help you.

806
01:01:47,770 --> 01:01:51,206
Oh, no, you don't. You hate me.
You've always hated me.

807
01:01:51,274 --> 01:01:53,936
That's why I'm here now.
It's all your fault.

808
01:01:54,010 --> 01:01:57,002
Maybe it's my fault,
but it's not because I hate you.

809
01:01:57,080 --> 01:01:59,446
Oh, I wish we could
be good friends.

810
01:01:59,515 --> 01:02:02,040
- You couldn't be a friend of mine.
- Why not?

811
01:02:02,118 --> 01:02:03,608
Because you don't get along
with Larry.

812
01:02:03,686 --> 01:02:05,677
He's the most intimate friend I've got
in the world...

813
01:02:05,755 --> 01:02:07,188
and you're against him.

814
01:02:07,256 --> 01:02:12,284
No, I'm not. Mr. Carmichael fired me
because I stood up for him.

815
01:02:12,361 --> 01:02:14,295
- You did?
- Mm-hmm.

816
01:02:14,363 --> 01:02:17,696
And I had nothing to do with you being
sent here. I didn't even know about it.

817
01:02:17,767 --> 01:02:21,430
Why, you didn't see me at
the court hearing, did you?

818
01:02:23,172 --> 01:02:25,572
Larry always said as soon
as he could get rid of you...

819
01:02:25,641 --> 01:02:27,871
he's gonna take me
and Gramp to Venice.

820
01:02:27,944 --> 01:02:30,139
That's in Italy.

821
01:02:30,213 --> 01:02:32,841
He thought maybe over there
they'd leave him alone.

822
01:02:32,915 --> 01:02:36,214
That's the ambition of his life...
to be let alone.

823
01:02:36,285 --> 01:02:39,049
Do you know
the ambition of my life?

824
01:02:39,122 --> 01:02:43,616
To get you to like me and trust me
and not run away every time you see me.

825
01:02:43,693 --> 01:02:46,093
- But l...
- Come closer.

826
01:02:46,162 --> 01:02:48,255
I want to tell you something.

827
01:02:48,331 --> 01:02:50,925
Oh, no, real close.
It's a secret.

828
01:02:52,401 --> 01:02:56,064
Promise never to tell
a living soul, especially Larry.

829
01:02:56,139 --> 01:02:58,107
Well...

830
01:02:58,174 --> 01:03:00,301
I like Larry very much.

831
01:03:01,344 --> 01:03:05,508
And I like you too.
I always have.

832
01:03:05,581 --> 01:03:08,072
Oh, Miss Sprague.

833
01:03:13,089 --> 01:03:15,649
- Perhaps he's asleep.
- I'll see.

834
01:03:36,913 --> 01:03:38,847
Oh, dear!

835
01:03:41,317 --> 01:03:43,877
Look, Crowbar, you know all
the circus people around here.

836
01:03:43,953 --> 01:03:47,150
You round them up to play a benefit
at the orphanage. I'll do the rest.

837
01:03:53,729 --> 01:03:55,720
- Mrs. Howard.
- Good afternoon.

838
01:03:55,798 --> 01:03:57,732
It was so generous
of the carnival people...

839
01:03:57,800 --> 01:04:00,200
to come here and give
this show for the children.

840
01:04:00,269 --> 01:04:02,396
They're having
the time of their lives!

841
01:04:53,456 --> 01:04:55,981
Why aren't you down in the yard
with the rest of the children?

842
01:04:56,058 --> 01:04:58,049
I wanna stay up here.

843
01:04:58,127 --> 01:05:01,119
The circus people have been kind enough
to give a special show for us.

844
01:05:01,197 --> 01:05:04,132
- It'll be starting in a few minutes.
- I don't care.

845
01:05:04,200 --> 01:05:08,193
The yard's full of clowns
and jugglers and acrobats.

846
01:05:08,271 --> 01:05:10,432
Bet there's a cage
full of wild animals.

847
01:05:10,506 --> 01:05:13,066
I hope they run loose
and kill a few people.

848
01:05:13,142 --> 01:05:17,135
There's a golden chariot
and performing pigs...

849
01:05:17,213 --> 01:05:21,081
and the fattest woman in the world
and the tallest man.

850
01:05:21,150 --> 01:05:23,084
I'm sure you'd have
an awfully good time.

851
01:05:23,152 --> 01:05:25,712
How can you have a good time
when your heart's breaking?

852
01:05:25,788 --> 01:05:28,655
- Hearts do not break.
- That's all you know about it.

853
01:05:28,724 --> 01:05:30,954
I take it, then,
you don't intend to come down.

854
01:05:31,027 --> 01:05:35,657
No, I swore I'd never leave this room
till they carried me out dead!

855
01:05:36,832 --> 01:05:39,767
Well, good-bye then.

